{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558388/1937120401/0363.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER\nProbable rain tonight; Sunday\nshower* followed by colder weath\ner afternoon or ni ght.\n(Dti* Sumps -ZsVurs\nLargest Daily Circulation of Any Newspaper i n North Carolina in Proportion to Population\nGOOD AFTERNOON\nThe move for paper money\nprinted in different colors teem*\nsuperfluous with \u00abo many budget*\nalready in the red.\nVOI\n.Ma 9on\nHENDERSONV1LLE, N. C., SATURDAY, DECEMBER 4, 1937\nSINGLE COPIES, FIVE CENTS\nFARM BILLS UNDER FIRE IN TWO HOUSES\nFRENCH BLOCK\nPASSAGE IN\nNEW INCIDENT\nCrisis Simmers Down; As\nsume Formal Apology\nMade to Marines\nJAPS NOT CERTAIN OF\nFOREIGN BOUNDARY\nCopvright. 1937, by United Pre\u00bb\u00bb\nSHANGHAI. Dec. 1. (l'P>\u2014\nJapanese advance units today\nwere within 35 units of Nanking:, j\na Japanese spokesman asserted.\nMeantime in Shanghai. Japa\nnese soldiers were involved in an\nother tense incident with foreign\ntroops, following on the heels of\nyesterday's situation in which they\nwithdrew from the U. S. Marines\ndefense sector in the International\nSettlement.\nFrench police, backed by arm\nored French cars, halted five Japa\nnese military trucks when they\ntried to pass through the French\nconcession bund en route from\nHongkew. Japanese section of the\nInternational Settlement, to N'an\ntao, old Chinese city between the\nconcession and tho Whangpoo\nriver.\nFifty French police barred the\nway when the trucks sought to\nenter the concession. Leaders of\nthe two groups stood m the street\narguing hotlv over the situation\nThree French armored cars were\nimmediately behind tike i>oIi\u00ab.e.\ntheir guns pointed towards the\nJapanese trucks.\nThe French forces consisted of\nsteel helmeted Annamites with\nfixed bayonets. The Japanese\nnumbered 35 soldiers armed with\nrifles and several off-cers.\nFrench authorities granted per\nmission for the Japnnese to pass\nthrough earlier provided they were\nunarmed, but tho convoy was halt\ned when it was discovered the\nJapanese were carrying weapons.\nA Japanese officer photograph\ned the scene while a colleague ar\ngued vigorously.\nThe Japanese army yesterday\nmade its first retreat during the\nfour-months-old Chinese-Japanese\nwar rather than risk a clash with\nmore than 3.000 seasoned fighters\nof the United States Marine\nCorps.\nA group of Japanese authori\nties today visited Brig. Gen. John\nC. Beaumont, Marino*' command\nant. presumably to tender forma!\napologies for the action of their\ninfuriated soldiers for the en\ncroachment on the American de\nfense sector of Shanghai's Inter\nnational Settlement.\nThe Japanese yesterday assert\ned the invasional was \"uninten\ntional\" and that they were un\nfamiliar with the settlement boun\ndary lines. It followed wild scenes\nwhen a Chinese Ultra-Nation\nalist hurled a hand-grenade into a\nmilitary demonstration the Japa\nnese armed forces were conduct\ning in the heart of the Anglo\nAmerican area of the settlement.\nGen. Beaumont was inclined to\naccept the apology and it was\nhoped the incident would be end\n(Continued on page four)\nFranco's Forces\nBreak Loyalists'\nLine In Aragon\nHENDALE. Dee. 4. (UP).\u2014\nLoyalist airplanes today vir\ntually wrecked nationalist for\ntifications at Alraur.devar, on\nthe Arogon front in retaliation\nfor the nationalist bombing* of\ninland loyalist towns.\nHENDAYE, Franco Spanish\nFrontier, Dec. 4. (UP).\u2014A day\nlong artillery bombardment fol\nlowed by a hand-to-hand battle\nwith trench knives and rifle butts\nyesterday smashed one of the\nloyalists' most heavily fortified\npositions on the upper Aragon\nfront, insurgent frontier dis\npatches reported. Hand-to-hand\nfighting lasted more than two\nhours.\nBefore dawn Generalissimo\nFrancisco Franco's heavy artil\nlery, drawn up on the snow-cov\nered slopes north of Sabinanigo\nto the east of his Jaca base, began\nhammering the loyalists' concretc\nline of fortifications around Oli\nvan.\nLarge holes were ripped in the\ngovernment line, for weeks a\nthreat to Franco's Jaca Huesca\ncommunications, and a large.part\nof the loyalist defenders were re\nported to have retreated before\nthe insurgent infantry attacked.\nc\nOver fhe Top in Rout of Chinese at Shanghai\nOnce the Japanese juggernaut got Shanghai's defenders on the move, nothing could be permitted to\nstop it. Through swamps, across makeshift bridges, over obstacles, troops and machines rumbled in\npursuit of retreating Chinese. With a tank leading: the way across the tottering bridge, Japanese\nfoot soldiers hurry to come to grips with tho enemy.\nST. JAMES IN\nDINNER EVENT\n90 Members and Visitors\nTake Part in Annual\nParish Affair\nThe members of St. James Epis\ncopal church held their annual\nparish dinner at the Henderson\nville Inn on Friday night. Ninety\nmembers of the church here and\nfrom St. John the Baptist. Up\nward, and St. Paul's, Edneyville,\ntogether with others, were among\nthe guests. Kev. George Floyd\nRogers, rector of Trinity church,\nAsheville. was the chief speaker.\nRev. Mr. Rogers outlined the\nwork of the church, his key\nthouKht being that the \"heart of\nthe Christian church is Christ.\"\nBut he showed Christ as a;i ex\nponent of determined principal\nand law as well as of divine traits\nof character that made Him lov\nable.\nAmong the items of the recent\ntriennial convention recited by the\nspeaker was the fact that a large\ngathering of Chinese and Japa\nnese native Episcopal bishops,\nmissionaries and church workers\nhad united in a communion ser\nvice exclusively for them during\n1 the progress of the convention.\nRev. Mr. Rogers' estimate of\nthe work of the pastor, Mr. Burke,\nand his repetition of a high esti\nmate placed upon him by the dean\nof the theological institution which\nRev. Mr. Burke attended drew a\nround of applause.\nIncident to the dinner, which\nwas arranged by the every-mem\nber canvass committee, Frank A.\nEwbank, A. S. Truex ami H. K.\nScheper, Mr. Ewbank read the\nproposed budget for the ensuing\nyear, and the first pledges for the\nbudget were made. The commit\ntee will arrange to reach others\nwho were not present last night,\nfor a continuance of the canvass.\nRoosevelt Goin?\n1 Home For More\ni Care In Abscess\nWill Land in Miami To\nmorrow: Condition Not\nAlarming, However\nI MIAMI, Fla., Dec. 4. (UP).\u2014\nThe effects of a tooth infection\nlast night forced President Roose\nvelt to cut short his sea-going\nvacation off the Florida coast in\norder to seek further treatment at\nthe hands of Washington special\nists.\nMr. Roosevelt who informed\nSecretary Man-in H. Melntvre\nhtat while his general health was\nexcellent, the delayed^ healing of\nthe gu mfrojn which an abscessed\nmolar had been extracted brought\nabout the decision to return to\n(Continued on page three)\nDemand Renewed\nU S. Troops Quit\nAsia's War Zone\nStrict Neutrality Advocates\nSee Continued Danger\nin Policy\nWASHINGTON, Dec. (UP)\nCongressional advocates of strict\nneutrality last night renewed their\ndemands that U. S. troops be with\ndrawn from tin* Sino-Japanese war\nzone after American Marines al\nmost clashed with Japanese troops\nin the international Settlement in\nShanghai.\nSen. Gerald P. Nye, K., N. D\u201e\nleader of the senate mandatory\nneutrality bloc, said the troops\nshould not have been sent to the\nsettlement \"in the first place.\nSen. Bennett C. Clark, D., Mo.,\nwarned that every day American\nsoldiers remain in China there is\n\"danger of embroiling the whole\nnation.\"\nTheir comment came after the\nstate department had expressed\ngrave concern over the narrow\nmargin by which a serious inci\ndent between the Japanese and\nAmerican troops had been avert\ned. While official comment was\nreserved pending receipt of dis\npatches from American Consul\nGeneral Clarence E. Gauss at\nShanghai, Secretary Cordell liu 1\nsaid that American officials at\nShanghai and Tokyo had warned\nthe Japanese of the inadvisabuity\nof holding the victory parade\nwhich precipitated the incident.\nCARL H.HYDER\nFUNERAL SET\nWill Be Held From Refuge\nBaptist Church Sun\nday at 2 P. M.\nCarl Hampton Hyder, 43, for\nmer resident of the Dana section,\ndied in Morpanton yesterday af\nternoon after an illness of 11\nFuneral services will be held at\nRefuge Baptist church Sunday\nafternoon at 2 o'clock, Key. Cole\nofficiating. Pallbearers will be\nDewey, Doll and Ed Sherman,\nWalter Hyder, Knox Hyder and\nGeorge Burgess.\nFlower girls, nieces ot the de\nceased are Elsie Emler, Mrs. Carl\nBrown, Mrs. R. M. Kerns, Thelma\nStepp, Geneva Floyd and Maiga\nU Mr'Hyder was the son of the\nlate Mr. and Mrs. J. V Hyder and\nis survived by his w\u00bbdo* a\nchildren, Clarence, Edna, Doi<th>\nand Vauda Hyder and L. C.\n'^Brothers surviving are Henrv,\nGovan and SporReon Hyder. and\nsurviving sisters are Delia ll>du\nand Mrs. John \\Natkins.\nD. T. CLEMENT\nRITES SUNDAY\nSon of Mrs. E. E. Clement\nWill Be Given Burial\nat Inman, S. C.\n___ I\nFuneral services for I). T. Clom\ncnt, 38, who died in Patton Memo\nrial hospital last night about 7 :U0\no'clock, will bo conducted on Sun\nday afternoon at 1 :.S0 o'clock at\nInman, S. C.\nServices are in charge of Stepp's\nFuneral Home, and the funeral\ncortege will leave the Stepp Home\nat 12 :\u00ab*{0 o'clock.\nMr. Clement had been ill for\nsome time and entered the hos\npital yesterday morning. He was\na son of Mrs. E. K. Clement, who\nresides on the Flat Rock road.\nUntil several weeks ago ho was\nengaged in business in Greenville,\nS. C. His mother has resided here\nfor a number of years.\nIK- is survived by his mother,\nhis widow, Mrs. Beatrice Looper\nClement, one brother, K. K. Clem\nent. Jr., of Greenville, and two\nsisters, Miss Evelyn Clement, of\nOcala, Fla., and Miss Virginia\nClement, of Hendersonvillc.\nWillow Rd. Home\nOf Louis Anders\nIs Total Fire Loss\nA fire on Thursday night de\nstroyed a house on the Willow\nroad, owned by Louis Anders, and\nthe loss today was estimated at\nabout $4,000, partiallv covered by\ninsurance.\nThe house was not occupied at\nthe time, but was completely fur\nnished. Origin of the blaze was\nnot determined. The house was\nlocated outside the city limits.\nMail Robbery With Loss High As\n$2,000,000 Probed After WPA Man\nFishes Mail Bag From East River\nNEW YORK. Doo. 4. (UP)\nA former WPA worker who was\nfishing for eels in the East liver\nfound himself the center of an in\nvestigation through which police\nand postal inspectors hoped to\nsolve the mysterious robbery of\na United States mail truck loaded\nwith valuable packages and regis\ntered mail.\nPeter Schieb, 40, dropped a line\ninto the river and pulled up a can\nvas mail sack nearly filled.\nHe notified police who fished\nout four more sacks.\nPostal inspectors said the truck\nwas robbed Thursday nighi but\nrefused to admit how much was\nlost. Estimates of the value in\nvolved ranged upward from $7,\n500 to $2,000,000.\n257 PERSONS\nRECEIVE GIFT\nCERTIFICATES\n2500 People Out for Win\ndow Shopping as Buying\nSeason Opens\nINAUGURAL BEYOND\nALL EXPECTATIONS\nOut of u crowd of about 2500\npeople who shopped Henderson*\nville store windows last night at\nth<? beginning of the Christmas\nseason, 257 persons received Rift\ncertificates of $1 each, and today\nthe first of these certificates were\nbeing redeemed in the stores with\nthe compliments of the donors. In\naddition, 35 shoppers received\ntheater tickets.\nWhile only about one of every\nten window shoppers received a\ncertificate or theater ticket, the\ncrowd apparently enjoyed the\nevent, and today officials of the\nmerchants division of the chamber\nof commerce said the effort to at\ntract people to the business dis\ntricts so that they might get a\nglimpse of the merchandise that\nhas been stocked for the Christmas\ntrade was successful even beyond\ntheir expectations.\nWith the colored street lights\nturned on for the first time, with\nChristmas trees lining tin* streets,\nwith attractively decorated win\ndows ablaze with light, and with\nthe high school band giving a\nconcert the evening, despite cold\nweather, was termed an enjoyable\nand profitable one.\nEight unidentified persons\nseven women and one man\u2014pass\ned out the gift certificates and\ntheater tickets. As they did so\nthey requested the participants to\n\"keep it to yourself.\" For perhaps\nan hour few persons could be\nfound who admitted having re\nceived certificates, but later many\nwere exhibited in the crowd on the\nstreets and in drug and other\nstores that were open. Although\nthe certificates may be redeemed\nat any time this month, scores\nwere turned in today, merchants\nsaid.\n\"The window displays which\nwere on view last night certainly\nshould convince anyone that Hen\n(iersonville merchants are well\nstocked for the Christmas traue\nand that no one need go else\nwhere to fill Christmas gift lists,\"\n11. K. Mitchell, chairman of the\nmerchants' division, said today.\n\"Of course the merchandise in\nthe windows was only a small\nfraction of the thousands of items\non display in the stores, and while\nthe merchants very much appre\nciate the response of the public\nlast night, they are very anxious\nthat every person who came out\nlast night and everyone else in\nHenderson county and adjacent\ntrade territory who could not at\ntend last night's event should\n\"follow through\" by inspecting\nthe merchandise on view in the\nstores before making purchases.\nIn addition to 93 business firms\nwhose names were published yes\nterday, the Superior Laundry.\nDixie' Store and City Ice and\nStorage company donated gift cer\ntificates.\nHORSES FED TO LIONS\nNASHUA, N. H., Dec. 4. (UP).\nOnce cheered to the barrier, four\nrace-horses were thrown to the\nlions yesterday. John T. Benson,\nwild animal farm operator, said\nhe had paid $200 for the broken\ndown nags as fodder tor his lions.\nSeven bags of mail reportedly\nwere recovered from the Hudson\nriver last night as federal agents\ninvestigated the disappearance of\n11 sacks from a mail truck while\nen route from Now York to Wee\nhawken, N .J., on a ferryboat.\nIt was not learned immediately\nif the contents of the seven sacks\nreported recovered were intact.\nThe saeks disappeared from the\ntruck while they were being trans\nported to New Jersey for distri\nbution aboard trains. When the\ntruck arrived at the postoffice at\nthe railroad terminal, it was dis\ncovered that the lock on the rear\nof the truck had been opened\nwith a key and that the sacks\nwere missing.\nARMED C.I.O. ORGANIZER IS\nBEHIND WITNESS STAND WHEN\nLABOR BOARD HAS HEARING\nWinston Salem\nChoir Triangle\nEnds In Slaying\nWINSTON-SALEM, Dec. 4.\u2014I\n(UP)\u2014John A. Hartle. for-1\nmer storekeeper, was held without\nbond today for trial for the choir\n-\u2022laying of Walter Lee Smith, 54,\nbarber, and a fellow member with\nHartle's wife of a church choir.\nHartle said lie found Smith in\na room with his wife and shot\nh!m three times.\nFIND OF BODY\nREVEALS WIDE\nLIQUOR FEUD\nJoe Spann, Dead Man,\nUnder Indictment for\nOteen P. 0. Robbery\nEDGEFIELD, Dee. 4. (UP).\u2014\nDiscovery of a partly decomposed\nbody of a North Carolina boot\nlegger led authorities of two\nstates last night to investigate his\nslaying and a bloody feud be\ntween rival liquor runners plying\nbetween Asheville, and Augusta,\nVltt.\nThe body was that of Joe\nSpann, described as a bootlegger\nof Asheville. It was discovered\nyesterday buried in an unkept\nspot beside a creek 10 miles north\nof here. Officers were led to the\nfrrave by John Thomas Lane,\nPineville, Ky., who volunteered to\ntell officials he was with Spann\nat the time of the slaying, last\nSeptember 23.\nOfficers held Lane in jail at\nnearby Aiken and his companion,\nlisted as Clemson Carson, in jail\nat Asheville. No charges were\nfiled against the two men pend\ning further investigation of\nLane's story.\nLane, arrested at Waynesville,\nfor a traffic violation, while\ntraveling; in the dead man's auto\nmobile recently, said he and Car\nson were present when two\nlit|Uor runners, rivals of Spann,\nfollowed Spann to a lonely spot\non the road, forced him from the\nhighway and killed him by frac-1\nturing his skull and firing a pis\ntol bullet int ohis head.\nAfter witnessing the slaying\nand burial, Lane said he and Car\nson took Spann's automobile to\nAugusta, where they separated\nand he kept the car.\nLane denied any complicity in\nthe crime. He told officers he\nhad made several trips running\nliquqor during the past several\nweeks.\nSpann was under indictment in\nNorth Carolina for robbing the i\npostoffice at Oteen.\n11 ALLEN TO\nRETAINSTORE\nWill Operate at the Same\nStand Next Year Under\nLease From Chain\nI. W. Allen, merchant, an\nnounces that the Belk-Simpson\ncompany will not operate a store\nin Hendersonville during 1938.\nMr. Allen states that he has\nleased his quarters from the chain\nmerchants for 1938. His lease also\nincludes the store room facing on i\nFifth avenue and occupied by the\nFlower Artistry Studio.\nAnnouncement was made last\nspring that the Belk-Simpson;\nstore had leased quarters occupied\nby Mr. Allen and would occupy\nthem with the Fifth avenue store\nsometime in summer. Thoy gave j\n1 Mr. Allen time to liquidate his\nstock with the expectation of be\ni ginning here in the fall, but Mr.\nAllen has leased from them the\nbuilding for the coming year.\nW.N.C. CATTLE SALES\nASHEVILLE, Dec. 4. (UP).\u2014\nThe Western North Carolina\nlivestock commission market sold\napproximately $15,000 in cattle!\nduring one day recently. i\nBoard's Subpena of Maga\nzine Materials Telling\nStory of Hearing Will Be\nResisted\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 4. (UP)\nSen. H. Styles Bridges, R., N. H.,\nyesterday denounced the National\nLabor Relations board in the sen\nate as a menace to press freedom\nwhile a magazine editor challeng\ned the board's power to subpena.\nBridges attacked the board for\nits efforts to subpena magazine\nmaterial in which Hartley W. Bar\nclay, editor of a steel trade maga\nzine. bitterly criticized the board\nfor its conduct of the Wierton\nSteel company case.\n\"In mv judgment this is one of\nthe most open attacks on freedom\nof the press we've seen.\" Bridges\nsaid. \"It is one more typ'cal ar\nbitrary action by the board.\"\nAttorne-s for the board, insist\ning that the subpena was with:n\npowers granted by the Wagner\nnet, prepared to ask the eastern\nKentucky U. S. District court to\nvalidate the subpena and order\nBarclay to observe it.\nElisha Hanson, attorney for\nBarclay and Conover-Mast. pub\nlishers of the \"Mill and Factory\"\nmagazine in which the article ap\npeared, said the subpena repre\nsented an open and dangerous at\ntack on freedom of the press. He\nsaid Barclay had been instructed\nto defy the subpena.\n\"If efforts are made to fight\nour position in federal court,\"\nHanson said, \"they will be resist\ned and resisted to the utmost.\n\"I want to point out that the\nWeirton Steel compnay had no\nconnection with this magazine. It\nheld none of its stock. No Weir\nton advertisements ever had ap\npeared in the magazine. The ar\nticle was simply a matter of jour\nnalistic enterprise, similar to other\nattacks on the labor board.\"\nThe article said, in part:\n\"Highlights of rip-snorting com\nedy provide a welcome relief from\nthe depths of tragedy to which\ncertain phases of the trial have\nplunged.\n\"When the attorneys for the\nNLRB, with supercilious smirks,\nannounced during the trial that\nthe only statement upon which\nthey could agree with W eirton\ncounsel was 'that that table is a\ntable'\u2014CIO observers and Weir\nton loyal workers alike roared\nwith laughter.\n\"It was high comedy when the\nWeirton attorneys called atten\ntion to the fact that a CIO organ\nizer was standing behind the wit\nness chair wearing a large revolv\ner and an ammunition belt loaded\nwith ammunition.\n\"The biggest and most ironic\ncomedy of the whole thing is that\nwhen this Ogpu-like trial is con\ncluded and if the case goes to the\nsupreme court, the review of the\ncase will not and cannot be based\nupon whether or not a^ fair trial\nwas held because the W agner^ act\ndoes not provide for a fair trial.\"\nGrover C. Byers\nDies In Spokane\nWord has just been received\nfrom Spokane, Wash., of the death\nof Grover C. Byers, formerly of\nthis county. Announcement as to\nfuneral arrangements will appear\nlater. Mr. Byers was the son of\nthe late Mont L. Byers, a lifelong\nresident of this county.\nBREVARD WILL HAVE\nMIXED COURT TERM\nBREVARD, Dec. 4. (Special).\nThe December term of superior\ncourt will convene in Brevard\nMonday for the trial of civil and\ncriminal cases.\nJudge Felix Alley of Waynes\nville, will preside at the mixed\nterm, with Solicitor Clarence 0.\nRidings of Forest City, appearing\nfor the state in criminal actions.\nThe court calendar, as compil\ned by the Brevard Bar associa\ntion, calls for civil court to con\ntinue into the second week, with\nthe criminal docket to be complet\ned by the end of the first week.\nJurors have been summoned for\nboth weeks by Sheriff George D.\nShuford.\nWANTS RICE AGREEMENT\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 4. (UP).\nRepresentative Robert L. Mou\nton, D., La., said yesterday he\nwas urging Secretary of State\nCordell Hull to include rice in;\nthe proposed reciprocal trade j\nagreement with Great Britain.\nSENATE BLOC\nSEEKS AID TO\nTRADE FIRST\nBridges Suggests Business\nRevival Plan Take\nPrecedence\nHOUSE SADDLES ITS\nBILL WITH CHANGES\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 4. (Ul*>\nSenator King, D., Utah, offered\nan amendment to the senate farm\nbill restricting expenditures for\n\u2666he far reaching farm program to\n$500,000,000 today.\nMeantime Senator Vandenberg\nrenewed his attack on the meas\nure, denouncing the amendment\nnroviding that the secretary ol\n\"griculture shall deternrne the\ncharacter and necessity for expen\nditures under the act.\nA bloc of senators seeking im\nmediate legislative encouragement\nfo business thr\u00b0atened further de\n'ay on farm bill action today when\nSenator Kinir proposed an aid-t\u00ab>\nbusiness program.\nFacing bi-partisan oppo.vtion to\nthe crop control measure, admin\nistration leaders feirod that final\naction mieht not be obtained by\nthe middle of next week.\nAs the senate met for its fir\u00abt\nSaturday session, Majority Load\ner Alben W. Barkley said that\nthere was no plan to limit debate\ndespite the fact that votinjr on\ncommittee amendments has been\ndelaved two davs bv lengthy op\npos'tion speeches. There wa\u00ab some\ncloak room talk, however, that\nleaders might decide to hold night\nsessions.\nAlthough snenking on the farm\nbill, King will digress to propone\nmodificftt;en of the capital tfain*\nand undistributed profits taxes.\nHe will suegefct that the modifica\ntions be offered as an amendment\nto a house bill which would repeal\nthe salary publicity act and which\nis now pending before the senate.\nKing's speech was expected to\nstart the senate again on an ex\ntensive discussion of business con\nditions and the current recession.\nKing's proposals will be in line\nwith sentiments of various sena\ntors\u2014 that immediate considera\ntion should be given to the busi\nness situation.\nSen. H. Styles Bridges, R. N.\nH., has suggested that the f .rm\nbill be put aside.\n\"More important and more fun\ndamental at this time than the\n(Continued on page three)\nTwo Fliers Killed\nAs Miami Speed\nManeuvers Begin\nMIAMI, Fla., Dec. 4. IT).-\u2014\nDeath today crossed the names of\ntwo of America's best-known\nspeed pilots\u2014Rudy A. Kling ami\nFrank Haines from the entr>\nlists of remaining races on th\u00ab\u00ab\nprogram of the annual All-Amer\nican air maneuvers.\nKling and Haines plunged to\ndeath vesterday when their fast\nships went out of control at the\nfirst sharp turn of a .'<0 mil\u00bb\u00bb\nspeed event.\nThe double mishap occurred a\nhal fmile north of the air maneu\nvers stands, but in full view of\n7000 spectators who had watched\nthose two zoom away with six\nother contestants in the Silva\ntrophy race, feature event ot the\nafternoon\u2014and the 13th event on\nthe air carnival program.\nCHRISTMAS\nSUPERSTITIOHS\nEarly American Indians, con\nverted to Christianity, believed\nthat on the eve of the Holy Day\nthe deer (ell on their knees in\nworship of the Great Spirit;\nA\n'Till","height":"28020","width":"20751"}}
